/**
 * \page yac_compute_weights_page YAC Weight File Generation Tool
   \tableofcontents

MPI-parallel tool for computation and write of weights for a provided source
and target grid configuration to netCDF file.

\section yac_compute_weights_page_usage Usage

\code{.unparsed}
yac_compute_weights.x
    -s src_grid_config
    -t tgt_grid_config
    -o weight_file
    [-i interp_stack_config]
    [-d output_grid_file]
    [-T]

where:
    -s       a required argument specifying the source grid configuration
             (see grid configuration below)

    -t       a required argument specifying the target grid configuration
             (see grid configuration below)

    -o       a required argument specifying output weight netCDF file name

    -i       an optional argument specifying the interpolation stack
             configuration. The value is a JSON-formated string that follows
             the convention for the YAC configuration file
             (see YAC doxygen documentation on interpolation stack).
             Default value:

             [
               {
                 "conservative":
                   {
                     "order": 1,
                     "enforced_conservation": false,
                     "partial_coverage": false,
                     "normalisation": "fracarea"
                   }
               },
               {
                 "fixed":
                   {
                     "user_value": -1
                   }
               }
             ]

    -d       an optional argument specifying netCDF output grid file name,
             which will contain the source and target grid. This can this for
             debugging purposes. The generated file can be converted to VTK
             using the debug_grid2vtk.x tool. Using ParaView, this file can
             then be visualised.

    -T       an optional argument enabling the writing of run-time performance
             measurments to standart output

grid_config:
    icon,FILE,NAME
             ICON-formatted netCDF grid file
             where:
               FILE       grid file name
               NAME       grid name
    scrip,FILE,NAME,EDGE_TYPE,MASK_FILE
             OASIS-SCRIP-formatted netCDF grid file
             where:
               FILE       grid file name
               NAME       grid name
               EDGE_TYPE  grid edge type
                 gc: great circle edges
                 ll: lon/lat circle edges
               MASK_FILE  mask file name
    exodus,FILE,NAME,EDGE_TYPE
             EXODUS-formated NetCDF grid file
             where:
               FILE       grid file name
               NAME       grid name
               EDGE_TYPE  grid edge type
                 gc: great circle edges
                 ll: lon/lat circle edges
    reg2d,NAME,NLON,NLAT,MIN_LON,MAX_LON,MIN_LAT,MAX_LAT
             Regular lon/lat grid
             (edges follow either circles of constant longitude or
              latitude)
             where:
               NAME        grid name
               NLON        number of grid vertices in longitude direction
               NLAT        number of grid vertices in latitude direction
               MIN_LON     minimum longitude in degree
               MAX_LON     maximum longitude in degree
               MIN_LAT     minimum latitude in degree
               MAX_LAT     maximum latitude in degree
    reg2drot,NAME,NLON,NLAT,MIN_LON,MAX_LON,MIN_LAT,MAX_LAT
             Regular lon/lat grid with rotated north pole
             (all edges follow great circles)
             where:
               NAME        grid name
               NLON        number of grid vertices in longitude direction
               NLAT        number of grid vertices in latitude direction
               MIN_LON     minimum longitude in degree
               MAX_LON     maximum longitude in degree
               MIN_LAT     minimum latitude in degree
               MAX_LAT     maximum latitude in degree
               POL_LON: longitude of north in degree
               POL_LAT: latitude of north in in degree
\endcode

\section yac_compute_weights_page_examples Examples

Computes the weights for a
\ref interp_method_conserv "first order conservative interpolation" with a
\ref interp_method_fixed "fixed user-defined fallback value" from a
Cubed-Sphere-Mesh provided in a EXODUS-formated netCDF file to a regional
Regular Gaussian grid using four processes.

\code{.unparsed}
mpirun -n 4 ./yac_compute_weights.x \
  -s exodus,CSMesh_129.nc,CSMesh_129,gc \
  -t reg2d,reg2d,20,10,0,20,80,90 \
  -o CSMesh_129_to_reg2d.nc \
  -i "
[
  {
    \"conservative\": {
      \"order\": 1,
      \"enforced_conservation\": false,
      \"partial_coverage\": false,
      \"normalisation\": \"fracarea\"
    }
  },
  {
    \"fixed\": {
      \"user_value\": -1
    }
  }
]"
\endcode

Computes the weights for
\ref interp_method_nnn "1-Nearest-Neighbour interpolation" from an
ICON grid to a NEMO ORCA2 rotated-stretched logically-rectangular grid provided
via a OASIS-SCRIP-formated netCDF file.

It also writes out a debug grid file. The NEMO grid stored therein is then
converted into a VTK file and visualised using ParaView.

\code{.unparsed}
mpirun -n 8 ./yac_compute_weights.x \
  -s icon,icon_grid_R02B04.nc,iconR02B04 \
  -t scrip,grids.nc,torc,gc,masks.nc \
  -o iconR2B04_to_torc.nc \
  -d debug_grid.nc \
  -i "[\"nnn\"]"

./debug_grid2vtk.x -n torc -f debug_grid.nc -o torc.vtk

paraview torc.vtk
\endcode

\section yac_compute_weights_page_parallelisation Information on Parallelisation

The tool is parallelised using MPI and can be run with an arbitrary number
of processes. In case of very high resolution grids executing this tool on
multiple processes can reduce run-time and memory consumption per processes.

Grid files are read by multiple processes, if available (see
\ref io_config_detail).

\section yac_compute_weights_page_stacks Interpolation Stack Examples

This section lists a couple of interpolation stack configurations that were
tested by [CERFACS](https://cerfacs.fr/en/home/) during their evaluation
of the [YAC integration into OASIS3-MCT](https://cerfacs.fr/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/TR-CMGC-24-182_yac_in_oasis.pdf).

\subsection yac_compute_weights_page_stacks_avg First-order Non-conservative

-# \ref interp_method_avg with weighting based on barycentric coordinates,
    which interpolates most target points matching with the source grid
-# \ref interp_method_ncc interpolates target points falling into edges cases
   along mask or grid boundaries
-# \ref interp_method_nnn assignes the closest source point to all remaining
   target points

\code
[
  {
    "average":
      {
        "weighted": "barycentric_coordinate",
        "partial_coverage": true
      }
  },
  {
    "ncc":
      {
        "weighted": "distance_weighted",
        "partial_coverage": true
      }
  },
  {
    "nnn":
      {
        "n": 1,
        "weighted": "arithmetic_average"
      }
  }
]
\endcode

\subsection yac_compute_weights_page_stacks_hcsbb Second-Order Non-Conservative

-# \ref interp_method_hcsbb interpolates most target points matching with the
   source grid
-# \ref interp_method_ncc interpolates target points falling into edges cases
   along mask or grid boundaries
-# \ref interp_method_nnn assignes the closest source point to all remaining
   target points

\code
[
  "bernstein_bezier",
  {
    "ncc":
      {
        "weighted": "distance_weighted",
        "partial_coverage": true
      }
  },
  {
    "nnn":
      {
        "n": 1,
        "weighted": "arithmetic_average"
      }
  }
]
\endcode

\subsection yac_compute_weights_page_stacks_first_conserv First-Order Conservative

-# \ref interp_method_conserv interpolates target cells overlapping with
   the source grid
-# \ref interp_method_fixed assignes all remaining target cells a fixed
   user-defined value (`-1.0` in this case)

\code
[
  {
    "conservative":
      {
        "order": 1,
        "enforced_conservation": false,
        "partial_coverage": false,
        "normalisation": "fracarea"
      }
  },
  {
    "fixed":
      {
        "user_value": -1
      }
  }
]
\endcode

\subsection yac_compute_weights_page_stacks_second_conserv Second-Order Conservative

-# \ref interp_method_conserv interpolates target cells overlapping with
   the source grid
-# \ref interp_method_fixed assignes all remaining target cells a fixed
   user-defined value (`-1.0` in this case)

\code
[
  {
    "conservative":
      {
        "order": 2,
        "enforced_conservation": false,
        "partial_coverage": false,
        "normalisation": "fracarea"
      }
  },
  {
    "fixed":
      {
        "user_value": -1
      }
  }
]
\endcode

*/
